'Paris' (, ; ) is the capital and most populous city of France.

It is situated on the river Seine, in the north of the country, at the heart of
the Ãle-de-France region. Within its administrative limits (the 20
arrondissements), Paris has a population of about 2,230,000, and its
metropolitan area is one of the largest population centres in Europe, with more
than 12 million inhabitants, who are referred to as 'Parisians' ( or ;
(masculine) â or Parisiennes (feminine) â ).

An important settlement for more than two millennia, Paris had become, by the
12th century, one of Europe's foremost centres of learning and the arts and was
the largest city in the Western world until the turn of the 18th century. Paris
is today one of the world's leading business and cultural centres and its
influences in politics, education, entertainment, media, science, and the arts
all contribute to its status as one of the world's major global cities.

Paris and the Paris region account for more than 30% of the gross domestic
product of France and have one of the largest city GDPs in the world, with â¬607
billion (US$845 billion) in 2011.  Considered as green
and highly liveable, the city and its region are the world's leading tourism
destination, hosting four UNESCO World Heritage Sites and many international
organizations, including UNESCO and the European Space Agency.
